  <div id=3D"wrapper" class=3D"sv">
    <div id=3D"content">
      <h2 id=3D"175-surface-area-and-volume-of-triangular-prisms">17.5 Surf=
ace area and volume of triangular prisms</h2>
      <p>A triangular prism has two identical triangular bases and three re=
ctangular sides joined at right angles to the
        bases.</p>
      <div class=3D"figure">
        <img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/grade-8/su=
rface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-21.png">
      </div>
      <p>We can calculate the surface area of the prism by finding the area=
 of the triangular faces and the rectangular
        faces, and then adding them all together.</p>
      <p>The net of a triangular prism consists of two triangular faces and=
 three rectangular faces.</p>
      <div class=3D"figure">
        <img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/grade-8/su=
rface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-22.png">
      </div>
      <div class=3D"worked_example">
        <h2 id=3D"worked-example-177-finding-the-surface-area-of-a-triangul=
ar-prism" class=3D"title">Worked Example 17.7: Finding the
          surface area of a triangular prism</h2>
        <div class=3D"question">
          <p>Find the surface area of the triangular prism.</p>
          <div class=3D"figure">
            <img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/grade-=
8/surface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-23.png">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"sketch-and-label-the-net-of-the-triangular-prism">Sketc=
h and label the net of the triangular prism.
          </h3>
          <div class=3D"figure">
            <img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/grade-=
8/surface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-24.png">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"find-the-areas-of-the-middle-rectangle-in-the-net">Find=
 the areas of the middle rectangle in the net.
          </h3>
          \[\begin{align}
          \text{Area rectangle} &amp;=3D l \times b \\
          &amp;=3D 8 \times 12 \\
          &amp;=3D 96
          \end{align}\]
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"use-the-theorem-of-pythagoras-to-find-the-length-of-the=
-hypotenuse">Use the theorem of Pythagoras to
            find the length of the hypotenuse.</h3>
          <blockquote class=3D"note">
            <p>The theorem of Pythagoras is covered in detail in Chapter 15=
, but it states that the square of the
              longest side in a right-angled triangle is equal to the sum o=
f the squares of the other two sides. We use
              this theorem to work out the length of one side of a right-an=
gled triangle if given the other two sides.
            </p>
          </blockquote>
          <p>For the two smaller rectangular faces, we know that the breath=
 is \(12 \text{ cm}\) but we do not know the
            length. The length of a small rectangle is equal to the length =
of the hypotenuse of one of the right-angled
            triangles (orange line in diagram below) that is formed by the =
\(3 \text{ cm}\) height of the triangle.</p>
          <div class=3D"figure">
            <img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/grade-=
8/surface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-25.png">
          </div>
          <p>To use the theorem of Pythagoras for one half of the triangula=
r faces:</p>
          <p>Let the length of the longest side \(=3D x\)</p>
          \[\begin{align}
          x^2 &amp;=3D 4^2 + 3^2 \\
          x^2 &amp;=3D 16 + 9 \\
          x^2 &amp;=3D 25 \\
          x &amp;=3D 5
          \end{align}\]
          <p>The longest side is equal to \(5 \text{ cm}\).</p>
          \[\begin{align}
          \text{Area of small rectangles} &amp;=3D l \times b \\
          &amp;=3D 5 \times 12 \\
          &amp;=3D 60
          \end{align}\]
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"find-the-area-of-the-triangular-faces">Find the area of=
 the triangular faces.</h3>
          \[\begin{align}
          \text{The area of a triangle} &amp;=3D \frac{1}{2} b \times h \\
          &amp;=3D \frac{1}{2} (8 \times 3) \\
          &amp;=3D 12
          \end{align}\]
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"find-the-sum-of-the-areas-of-the-faces">Find the sum of=
 the areas of the faces.</h3>
          \[\begin{align}
          \text{Surface area of triangular prism} &amp;=3D 2(\text{area sma=
ll rectangle}) + (\text{area middle rectangle})
          + 2(\text{area triangle}) \\
          &amp;=3D 2(60) + 96 + 2(12) \\
          &amp;=3D 120 + 96+ 24 \\
          &amp;=3D 240
          \end{align}\]
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"write-the-final-answer">Write the final answer.</h3>
          <p>The surface area of the triangular prism is \(240 \text{ cm}^2=
\).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <section id=3D"m08-17-05a" class=3D"exercises interactive_questions" =
data-section-exercise-id=3D"m08-17-05a" data-exercise-number=3D"17.5">temp =
text</section>
      <h3 id=3D"calculating-volume-of-a-triangular-prism">Calculating volum=
e of a triangular prism</h3>
      <p>The volume of a triangular prism is calculated by multiplying the =
area of the triangular base by the height of
        the prism. To calculate the volume of a triangular prism, we must u=
se the triangular face as the base of the
        prism so that the cross section of the prism is uniform (in other w=
ords, the same shape and area all the way
        up).</p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Base: Triangular face <br> Cross section: Uniform</td>
            <td>Base: Rectangular face <br> Cross section: Not uniform</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/gr=
ade-8/surface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-26.png" alt=3D=
""></td>
            <td><img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/gr=
ade-8/surface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-27.png" alt=3D=
""></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class=3D"worked_example">
        <h2 id=3D"worked-example-178-calculating-volume-of-a-triangular-pri=
sm" class=3D"title">Worked Example 17.8: Calculating volume of
          a triangular prism</h2>
        <div class=3D"question">
          <p>Calculate the volume of the prism.</p>
          <div class=3D"figure">
            <img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/grade-=
8/surface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-28.png">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"use-the-formula-for-the-area-of-the-base">Use the formu=
la for the area of the base.</h3>
          \[\begin{align}
          \text{Area of triangle} &amp;=3D \frac{1}{2}(b \times h) \\
          &amp;=3D \frac{1}{2}(8 \times 10) \\
          &amp;=3D 40
          \end{align}\]
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"calculate-the-volume-of-the-triangular-prism">Calculate=
 the volume of the triangular prism.</h3>
          \[\begin{align}
          \text{Volume of prism} &amp;=3D \text{area of base} \times h \\
          &amp;=3D 40 \times 20 \\
          &amp;=3D 800
          \end{align}\]
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"write-the-final-answer-1">Write the final answer.</h3>
          <p>Volume of the triangular prism \(=3D 800 \text{ cm}^3\).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class=3D"worked_example">
        <h2 id=3D"worked-example-179-using-volume-to-find-an-unknown-length=
-of-a-triangular-prism" class=3D"title">Worked Example 17.9:
          Using volume to find an unknown length of a triangular prism</h2>
        <div class=3D"question">
          <p>The volume of the rectangular prism is \(1\ 650 \text{ cm}^3\)=
. Calculate the value of \(x\). All
            measurements are given in centimetres.</p>
          <div class=3D"figure">
            <img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/grade-=
8/surface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-29.png">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"write-the-formula-for-volume-of-a-triangular-prism">Wri=
te the formula for volume of a triangular
            prism.</h3>
          \[\begin{align}
          \text{Volume of prism} &amp;=3D \text{area of base} \times \text{=
height} \\
          &amp;=3D \frac{1}{2}(b \times h) \times h
          \end{align}\]
          <div class=3D"figure">
            <img src=3D"https://www.siyavula.com/read/za/mathematics/grade-=
8/surface-area-and-volume-of-3d-objects/images/figure-17-30.png">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"use-the-volume-of-the-rectangular-prism-to-find-the-val=
ue-of-x">Use the volume of the rectangular
            prism to find the value of \(x\).</h3>
          \[\begin{align}
          \text{Volume of prism} &amp;=3D 1\ 650 \text{ cm}^3 \\
          1\ 650 &amp;=3D \frac{1}{2} (44 \times 15) \times x \\
          1\ 650 &amp;=3D 330x \\
          5 &amp;=3D x
          \end{align}\]
        </div>
        <div class=3D"workstep">
          <h3 id=3D"write-the-final-answer-2">Write the final answer.</h3>
          <p>Height of the triangular prism \(x =3D 5 \text{ cm}\).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <section id=3D"m08-17-05b" class=3D"exercises interactive_questions" =
data-section-exercise-id=3D"m08-17-05b" data-exercise-number=3D"17.6">temp =
text</section>
    </div>
